<DocsLayout title="Creating the Backlog" description="Break the Vinyl Vault architecture into ordered tickets with API integration isolated.">
  <h1 class="mb-6">Creating the Backlog</h1>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Same process as P3 — architecture goes in, ordered tickets come out. Each ticket has clear acceptance criteria.</p>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">The prompt</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Paste this into Claude along with your architecture document:</p>

  <CodeBlock copy>{`Here is the architecture for an online record store:

[Paste your architecture]

Break this into ordered implementation tickets. Each ticket should have: a clear title, labels, size (S/M/L), dependencies, description, and specific acceptance criteria.

## Ordering
1. Infrastructure first (repo, Docker, database schema)
2. Backend — product catalog API, search
3. Stripe integration (isolated — its own ticket, not bundled with other backend work)
4. Frontend — product grid, search, cart
5. Integration — frontend calls backend, checkout flow end-to-end
6. Google Maps embed (can be independent)
7. Deploy
8. Polish and optimization

## Key constraint
API integration tickets (Stripe, Google Maps) must be SEPARATE from other tickets. "Add Stripe checkout" is its own ticket, not part of "Build the cart." This isolation makes verification easier — when you review a Stripe ticket, you're only looking at Stripe code.

Every API integration ticket must include this acceptance criterion: "All external API calls verified against official documentation."

Create the backlog as BACKLOG.md.`}</CodeBlock>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Review the backlog</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Same checks as P3, plus one new one:</p>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-text-secondary space-y-2 text-sm mb-6">
    <li><strong class="text-text">Dependency order</strong> — infrastructure before features, backend before frontend, cart before checkout</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">No scope creep</strong> — no tickets for features Marcus didn't request</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Acceptance criteria are verifiable</strong> — not "payment works" but "payment completes with Stripe test card 4242 4242 4242 4242 and order status updates to 'paid'"</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">API tickets are isolated</strong> — Stripe integration is its own ticket, Google Maps is its own ticket. Each can be verified independently against official docs.</li>
  </ul>

  <Callout variant="info">
    <p class="text-sm"><strong>Why isolate API tickets?</strong> When a Stripe ticket is bundled with cart logic, review becomes muddled — you're checking business logic and API correctness at the same time. Separate tickets mean separate reviews. When you open a Stripe PR, you focus entirely on verifying API calls against the docs.</p>
  </Callout>

  <div class="mt-8 p-6 bg-primary-bg rounded-lg border border-primary/20 text-center">
